snippet.textDisplay:
I am italian.
I've never seen an NBA match, I've never seen a Lakers match.
But in the nineties, basketball was a huge thing, and there were 3 names that we all knew:

Michael Jordan, Kobe Bryant, Shaquille O'Neal (and later, LeBron James, but it was already 2000's).

These were giants of the NBA.
Everybody knew about them.
Sunday evening I was at dinner with friends and colleagues, when one of them, looking at his phone, said "Kobe Bryant is dead?".
Me and him were the ONLY people, at that table, who knew who he was.
The news was shocking.
It was so sudden.
Too soon, just too soon.
That's... not how you should die. Just no.

snippet.textDisplay: Life is fragile, but legacies are permanent and unbreakable. Kobe's story, accomplishments, and mentality will continue to live on through his loved ones and fans. Don't take anything for granted and make sure you appreciate everyone that you have the privilege of coming into contact with. I'm guilty of still treating my loved ones poorly from time to time due to my pride and ego. Watching this video while typing this comment is filling my eyes up with tears and I hate how we, as human beings, need a tragedy to remind us of how we should conduct ourselves and treat those in our vicinity. Jealousy, animosity, wealth, and fame all lose meaning in the face of death. Although pursuing great things to make the most out of our time on Earth is meaningful and does indeed make us feel more content, it should never be done at the expense of others or even our happiness. In my opinion, death is never timely, so the term "untimely death" is actually nonsensical. Kobe would want all of us, those who love and care for him, to learn from everything and anything he does or that happens to him. I vow to make this tragedy a turning point in my life since that's the only way I can repay Kobe for what he means to me: a real-life Super Hero.
